post_text: Happy Friday! It's a beautiful day out there. Best wishes to everyone for a safe Labor Day weekend; there will be no school Monday. This is not a political post at all, but I want to share that Dr. Fauci lists Iowa as one of seven states to be cautious this weekend to avoid a spike in positive COVID-19 cases, and the positivity rate in Warren County is on the rise, along with many other counties. We have had a great start to school, and I want to keep that going! Please consider avoiding large gatherings and practice physical distancing when it is possible. Have a great weekend!

post_text: I just took a call from a parent whom I don't think I have interacted with before. He just called to say he appreciates everything the district is doing and supports the school 100%. I thanked him for taking the time to do that and told him that I really appreciated how our parents and community are showing support and extending grace right now as we try to navigate difficult situations together. That is one of the great things about Indianola: people step up and try to get through challenges together. I know we don't get everything right the first time or do a perfect job, but I am so proud of our staff in all different roles. They are working very hard and truly care about kids. Thank you so much to people who recognize that and comment on it. That's a real lift for everyone!

post_text: I'm sharing a graphic about the recent activity of our IT Department. They have been incredibly busy as technology demands skyrocketed this fall, simultaneously with the enrollment crunch. We appreciate everyone's patience and understanding as we work through things related to enrollment, remote learning, and the like. We are hearing great reviews of the interactive flat panels the district installed in all classrooms the end of last year, and our teachers are doing an awesome job of learning how to utilize them. Thanks, everyone, and kudos to our tremendous IT staff!

post_text:
Sharing a tool that United Way is helping to make possible:
United Way of Central Iowa has teamed up with Bright by Text, a national parent texting program, to put expert tips, educational games, and child development information directly into the hands of parents and caregivers of children prenatal through age eight for FREE. We need your help spreading the word!



Bright by Text message topics include brain development, learning activities, health, and more. Each message includes a link to a landing page with more details, short videos, and related resources from national expert partners like PBS, Vroom, Sesame Street, and the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Parents with children under age 8 can sign up by texting the word IOWAKIDS to 274448; or by visiting bbtxt.org/2Vt4J0W. Though the information is FREE and any resources or events are free or low-cost, standard text message and data rates apply.

Please note BBT is available in English and Spanish

post_text: The City has partnered with Central Iowa Shelter and Services, Helping Hand and the Chamber to bring a program to our community. “Indianola Eats” is a program funded by a grant and designed to support local restaurants impacted by COVID in providing hot meals to the community. Participating restaurants will be providing meals in the Dollar General parking lot (1803 W 2nd) every ‪Monday evening at 5pm‬ from through Sept 28. The program will have a soft-start on Monday, August 10th. There will be 100 meals provided and are on a first come basis.

City of Indianola #thinkindianolafirst
July 22 at 11:30 AM ·

Indianola’s Census response rate is currently at 71.1%. This week, the US Census Bureau will be sending reminder postcards to households who have not yet responded to the 2020 Census. This will be the final mailing before census takers begin visiting non-responding households in mid-August.
If you have not already responded to the Census, and to avoid a visit to your home by a census taker, please respond online (https://2020census.gov/en/ways-to-respond/responding-online.html) or by phone (844-330-2020) today.
#thinkindianolafirst
#everyonecounts
#shapeyourfuture

post_text:
Congratulations to Mrs. Pottebaum’s AP U.S. History Students and to Mrs. Pottebaum! Their hard work through a difficult fourth quarter of remote work showed up in their test scores:

IHS had 12 students tested, out of 2,031 statewide and 472,705 globally.

IHS students had a mean score of 3.92, compared to 2.65 statewide and 2.83 globally!

The percentage of IHS scores 3 or higher was 91.7%, compared to 52.7% statewide and 58.7% globally!

post_text: Students going into grade 10-12, please check your email for a survey about PowerSchool Class Pages. In a week we have a team of secondary teachers looking to standardize a template for teachers to use in hopes of making the virtual learning more fluid and having consistent expectations and practices in the high school and middle school virtual classrooms. This survey is a quick, 5 question long, inquiry into what students thought worked well and what didn't and the more data we can collect from students, the better.

post_text: One of the reasons we originally were hesitant about picking a later date for graduation was the creation of conflicts for graduates and their families. One of those significant conflicts was for students entering the various branches of the military. Some could make it June 28, and some could not. We appreciate all of them and their willingness to serve. We should have ensured they got named and mentioned but did not do that. This is Carter Luttrell, one of those graduates. There are a number of others. Please feel free to share photos if you like. This is a way to publicly thank and honor this part of our graduating class.

post_text:
Hello Seniors and Parents:

Just a quick reminder that Graduation ticket pick up is Tuesday, June 9 from 11:00 a.m.-2:00 p.m. and 5:00-7:00 p.m. in the circle driveway on the south side of the building (by the main office.) In case of inclement weather, we will be in the office. Both tickets will be in an envelope with your students' name on it. We ask that you distribute to whom will be attending the ceremony.

If you or your student haven't RSVP'd to inform us if they will be participating in the graduation ceremony please follow the link to complete:

https://forms.gle/zCLoTHgeccdMnG8n8.

We thank each of you for your effort and flexibility when dealing with this years' graduation. We've had many schedules this past month and half for you and your student that required some adjusting with your work and home schedules. It has not gone unnoticed and we appreciate you working with us.

post_text:
Congratulations to the following students for receiving the 2019/2020 Distinguished Achievement Award at the Indianola Middle School; Cailey Baker, Zach Benge, Elyse Bierman, Kaitlyn Bonnes, Emma Brown, Maggie Buttrey, Cray Coffey, Andrew DeWall, Suzanne Fredericks, Graham Hilton, Jade McCarthy, Cecilia McDonald, Alana Moser, Lauren Philippi, Madalyn Snow, and Peyton Wilbur.

These students had to complete specific portfolio requirements in the areas of citizenship, 3.0 GPA, STEM, service learning, fine arts, and career exploration for this award. Many students had to show perseverance and self-motivation to finish their portfolios after Covid-19 shut down the schools. Their hard work was evident in their work. Congratulations students of Indianola Middle School

8th grade quarter 4 students have taken Family and Consumer Science learning straight to home. We have been participating in weekly cooking videos of recipes that use fairly common household ingredients. If you are interested in any of these recipe videos, please contact Ms. Cordray at janaya.cordray@indianola.k12.ia.us

Week 1: introduction

Week 2: french toast

Week 3: box mix cookies

Week 4: pizza (we are here this week 5/4)

Week 5: calzones

Week 6: pigs in a blanket

Week 7: crescent taco bake

We have also been using skills to create a food truck digitally! Updates to come!

post_text:
I think this word is out to seniors and their parents, but I thought I would share again in case others are interested:

Tonight, April 20 we invite our fellow Indians to come together in their cars at Indianola Football Stadium as we turn on the stadium lights at 8:20 pm (20:20 military time) to honor all of our seniors who have had their final year of high school cut short.

When the lights go on, the scoreboard will be set for 20 minutes and 20 seconds. It is imperative that everyone stays in their own cars to remain safely socially distant.

Class of 2020, we love you and we honor you!

Tonight, April 20 we invite our fellow Indians to come together in their cars at Indianola Football Stadium as we turn on the stadium lights at 8:20 pm (20:20 military time) to honor all of our seniors who have had their final year of high school cut short.

When the lights go on, the scoreboard will be set for 20 minutes and 20 seconds. It is imperative that everyone stays in their own cars to remain safely socially distant.

Class of 2020, we love you and we honor you!

post_text:
This is a time of financial uncertainty for many; and while the school district is in a sound position, there are many unknowns as we move forward. In times like these, I think it is more important than ever to celebrate the bright spots. Here are a couple: last night the school board approved our budget for next year, which included a maximum levy rate of $17.99/$1,000. This is a reduction of
$.51/$1,000 from last year. The district also refinanced bonds from 2015 recently, resulting in more than $2,400,000 of savings in future interest. That is a reduction of 66% of future interest payments on those bonds. Since 2015 the district has refinanced and prepaid bonds multiple times, saving taxpayers over $7,000,000 in interest.

If this is the first time you have been to our bank there will be a small amount of paperwork needed. After the necessary information is collected the food items will be placed in your vehicle by one of our staff members. Thanks to Casey Brown and Jeff Siebersma for heading this up.

post_text:
Sharing information about Laura Ingalls Wilder Elementary's planned parade in case you haven't seen it:

LIW families,

Due to the expected rain on Friday, April 3rd the LIWilder parade has been moved to Saturday, April 4th at 10:30 AM. If the Governor issues a "Shelter in Place Order," then the parade will be postponed to a later date.

The following will be the route of the parade. By recommendations from our Indianola Police Department, we will not be crossing any major highways for the safety of our staff and others on the road.

Route--

Will begin at LIWider and make a loop in the neighborhood to the north of the building.

North on U street
West on Girard Ave
North on W street
East on Henderson Ave
South on U street again
After the loop we head head East on Euclid Ave

South on G street
East on Salem
finish by taking a loop around the square to end at Funaro's
We are looking forward to seeing all of our students and families during this time. We ask that everyone please practice social distancing during the parade.

Stay safe and healthy!



Mrs. Naughton

post_text:
Indianola CSD Community,

I recently saw another resource for learning at home, WideOpenSchool.org , that people might find helpful. By way of an update, I want people to know that lots of work, planning, and learning is going on behind the scenes right now. We want to provide continuous learning opportunities at home in the most practical ways while trying to ensure equity and access. We have some staff for whom online teaching and learning is pretty natural and others for whom it is brand new.

We want to stay connected and provide support to families, and we will keep communicating through the district website, this Facebook page, and the district notification system.

Hang in there, everyone! We will get through this and will learn new things and build capacity along the way.

Indianola Middle School counselors recognize that as we navigate through the next few weeks, you and your family might be experiencing a variety of emotions. We have put together some resources that we have sent to students and parents to help cope with stress that they may be experiencing (please see link below). This week, we are focusing on mindfulness as a way to ease difficult emotions. We plan to continue to send out a variety of resources over the next couple of weeks. In the meantime, please feel free to reach out to us. We miss everyone at school and can't wait to be with you again.

Again, please do not hesitate to reach out to one of the counselors at the middle school. Below is our contact information:

post_text: We have been advised by the Iowa Department of Education, Bureau of Food and Nutrition, that students must be physically present to receive grab-and-go meals. We have reached out to the Governor’s Office to reconcile this mandate with Governor Reynold’s March 23 recommendation that families “send just one family member out for errands.” Pending further guidance, we are unable to provide lunches to parents whose children are not with them.

This community does a great job of pulling together and supporting each other. Thank you to everyone doing thoughtful things even as we try to isolate to flatten the curve of COVID-19.

I just saw video of Music Teacher Natalie Gordon and Emerson Principal Mark Timmerman performing "Tuesday Tunes" for kids, which was awesome! I know our staff want to stay connected with students and it is very frustrating to everyone to have to be apart. Find the positives in a situation none of us chose, and we will get through this in good shape!

post_text: If you see this article or anything like it, please understand that it is outdated. Please rely on the school district website, this Facebook page, or direct email from the school for up to date information. Again, this article is outdated. Thank you

post_text:
Thank you to everyone who is doing their part with social distancing in an attempt to flatten the curve of new COVID-19 cases! The next couple of weeks are going to tell us a lot about the pandemic's spread in our area. Remember that you can call 2-1-1 if you have questions. United Way is working the phones. If you are experiencing symptoms, call your doctor for a phone assessment first. If it becomes necessary for you to be tested, that happens by referral according to State Hygienics Lab guidance.

As families return from Spring Break, please be very vigilant for symptoms and consider self-quarantining.

This whole situation is surreal, but the way we conduct ourselves in the coming weeks can have a big impact on how we get through the pandemic. Thanks again for your caution.

post_text: RESULTS ARE IN: The Indianola High School Academic Decathlon team took home eighth place out of 12 teams at the March 6-7 State Tournament in Waterloo. Indianola earned a total of 26,164 points. Junior Jared Overmann took home a bronze medal in math in the honors large division. Sophomore Noah King earned a gold medal in math in the varsity large division, as well as a bronze medal in economics in the varsity large division. Senior Jillian Norton won the silver medal in math in the varsity large division.

An update from the Indianola CSD IT Department:

Late yesterday afternoon, the district sent out an email to all parents, guardians and staff regarding this update (https://www.indianola.k12.ia.us/2020/03/coronavirus-update/) on the Coronavirus. We are aware that some of you did not get that message until several hours later. We have been in contact with our messaging provider and they are fully aware of the issue and are actively working to make changes to improve the communication speed. The provider indicated that they were hit with over 10 times their highest volume yesterday and that it may take through the weekend to resolve. While we will continue to communicate any Coronavirus updates through email, we encourage all staff, parents, and guardians to actively check our website, www.indianola.k12.ia.us , for updates. I will also post updates on Facebook.

post_text: Side One and Flip Side wrapped up their competition season on a high note! The groups traveled to Totino-Grace in Fridley, MN where they faced groups from 4 states. Flip Side came home with the 2nd place trophy in the daytime prep division! Side One placed 4th in the daytime field which advanced them to finals. In the evening finals, they were able to hold their ground and came home with the 3rd Runner-Up trophy! Thank you to all our fans who came to the competition and to those of you at home cheering us on via livestream! A special thanks to Clark and Anika Jackson for driving the equipment trailer and to our parents who chaperoned the event. Don't forget our FINAL SHOW CHOIR CONCERT is Tuesday, March 10, at 7pm in the HS Auditorium!

post_text: Mr. Richardson and the IHS Wind Ensemble recently Skyped with composer Randall Standridge from Jonesboro, Arkansas. The band is studying Standridge's composition entitled "The Nine." The composition is about the story of the Little Rock Nine from the fall of 1957. A few students were able to ask Standridge some questions about the composition and the life of a full-time composer. The band performed part of the piece for Standridge and received a brief critique from him. It was an amazing opportunity for our students! You can hear "The Nine" as well as several other selections at the upcoming IHS Band Concert on Monday, March 9. The concert features the Symphonic Band and Wind Ensemble starts at 7 PM in the Indianola HS auditorium. Admission is $3 for adults & $2 for students. Hope to see you there!

post_text: The IHS show choirs had a great weekend at the Marion Competition! Side One finished 1st Runner-Up in the finals! They earned 2nd place in 4A during the daytime round. Two incredible performances from them! Flip Side took first place in the prep division and also came home with the "Best Vocals" caption award for the prep division! A big thank you to our unsung heroes of the day, our 8 wonderful bus drivers, 9 chaperones, trailer driving crew, and numerous parent and family supporters that came out to cheer us on! It takes a village and Indianola knows how to bring one! We will wrap up our competition season with the Totino-Grace competition in Fridley, MN on March 7 and will finish with our last concert on Tuesday, March 10, 2020 at 7pm in the IHS Auditorium.

post_text: Mrs. Wolf's class shopped for their Cafe food items this week. In addition to their Coffee service once a quarter, they invite their parents and staff to join them for lunch. The students send out a survey that collects interest level; then they incorporate their math skills to calculate the amount of food they will need to feed their guests. In the store they shop the best deal that matches their budget and serving proportions. On Friday, they will serve this lunch.

post_text: We had a gentleman come in yesterday to make a generous donation to our Food Service Department. He doesn't want accolades, so I won't name him, but I want to mention what he said. He shared that his wife and he discussed that they didn't need to spend money on Valentine's Day, and they decided to make a gift instead. Their gift will help a lot of students who have zero or negative lunch account balances. Others have generously donated to Food Service, too, and I know there are many other needs in the community besides that. I really appreciate the many giving people out there!

post_text: These IHS students were accepted to the ISU Honor Choir that was held at ISU in Ames, IA on February 9-10, 2020. They were selected from 6 auditions sites around the state of Iowa through a private audition with Dr. James Rodde, Director of Choral Activities at ISU. The audition included singing a solo, sight-reading, pitch retention, and key signature identification. It is an elite choir with only 98 singers being accepted from across the entire state. Congrats to (2nd row) Wilson Sandquist, Gabe Buthmann, Ben Richardson, Liam Christensen, (1st Row) Jessica Anderson, Casey Daughenbaugh, and Terrill Hagener.

post_text: The Little Hawkeye Conference Honor Band took place on Monday, February 10 at Norwalk High School. 23 9th-12th grade students represented Indianola at the festival, covering nearly every band instrument and making up one of the largest represented schools at the festival! Great job, band students!

Sharing from Teacher Mentor Coordinator Stacy Evans:
New teachers had the time and opportunity to gain insight and network with teachers from around the state today. They had opportunities to share their perspectives on relevant topics. It was inspiring to hear the stories and journey of Iowa’s past and present Teachers of the Year. We also heard from a student panel that emphasized the POWER of that “one teacher” as well as mental health and self care.

Blake Dowson came to Mrs. Singleton's 3rd grade class for their January Growth Mindset Celebration. He talked about how he uses a growth mindset as a baseball scouting writer for Perfect Game and in other areas of his life. 4 students were recognized for showing a growth mindset this month!

The Indianola High School Academic Decathlon team competed in the Des Moines Regional Competition on Tuesday, January 21! The team scored a total of 23,758 points, which was good for sixth place out of 15 large schools competing!

Individual honors were awarded to the following students:

-Noah King: varsity second place in economics, varsity third place math.

-Paige Huntley: scholastic second place economics, scholastic first place interview, scholastic overall second place.

-Nautica Frye: scholastic third place in math, scholastic third place in music.

-Jillian Norton: varsity third place social science.

-Anja Waugh: honors third place speech.

Thank you Lieutenant Rob Hawkins for sharing some of his experiences as a soldier in the Middle East. Kevin Huss’ and Susan Pottebaum’s 20th Century World History classes are studying how the terror attacks of September 11, 2001 have changed world politics and have impacted us as Iowans.

Lieutenant Hawkins served 22 years in the Army Reserves and was deployed five times including in Kuwait, Iraq and Afghanistan.

post_text: The IHS Spanish Club participated in the Pulsera Project in December. The Pulsera Project is a non-profit organization that sells bracelets through high schools across the country in order to raise money for artisans in Nicaragua and Guatemala. Profits from bracelet sales provide these artisans with housing, healthcare, sustained work, scholarships and more. The students raised $1,300! Their top sellers were Modesto Segura and Peyton Belt.

Indianola Project Graduation Committee is sponsoring a Jingle Bell Jamboree for kids of all ages on December 14 from 11 am to 3 pm at the Blake Fieldhouse in Indianola (see attached flyer).

This is a new holiday event for the community.The Jamboree will have 13 different inflatables (bounce houses, obstacle courses, etc.). There will be a Candyland display, pizza, and lots of holiday treats available. Santa will be at the event for pictures and fun with the kids. This is a great holiday event with all proceeds going to sponsor a safe, fun activity for the graduating seniors of Indianola. Cost is $10 per child, adults are free.

Kate Jauron-Flute, Cheyenne Torres-Clarinet, Nate Gerber-Trombone, Abby Voshell-Clarinet, Soren Christensen-French Horn, Kyle Roberts-Trombone & Cannon Roberson-Percussion.

The honor band is Saturday, January 11, 2020 at Ankeny HS. Congrats, band students!

post_text:
Last week in Mrs. Singleton's third grade classroom at Emerson, the class held their end of the month Growth Mindset Celebration. Simpson College Men’s Basketball Head Coach Bjorkgren and Women's Assistant Basketball Coach Lonning were invited to be the guest speakers. They shared their personal insight about Growth Mindset and how they have used Growth Mindset in their lives. Coach Lonning also read the book Our Mighty You, which her mother authored. The book is about the trials and tribulations of Coach Lonning's life as a child growing up.
Two students were awarded Growth Mindset certificates for demonstrating a Growth Mindset for the month of November.

Indianola CSD Stakeholders,
Please read this request and participate:

Our school district has requested a Needs Assessment Survey conducted by the Iowa Association of School Boards (IASB). The survey is designed to help us assess our strengths and areas of needed improvement, with a focus on improved student achievement. We would like your opinions and judgments in response to the brief survey linked below. The survey takes an average of 9 minutes to complete. All responses are anonymous.

Just click the link below, or paste it in your browser and follow the instructions. Thank you for your participation and helping to make improvements for our students. Please reply with any questions.

http://lsurvey.ia-sb.org/index.php?r=survey/index&sid=91917&lang=en

Thank you!

Indianola Child Care is currently hiring energetic individuals interested in working with school age children before and/or after school. Applicants need to be at least 18 years of age. Before school positions begin at 6:00, 6:15, 6:30 or 7:00 and end at 8:00. Afternoon positions begin at 2:30 (1:30 on Wednesdays) and end at 5:00, 5:15, 5:30 or 6:00. Hourly rate $10.15-14.30.

Please apply on the District website www.indianola.k12.ia.us under Departments, Human Resources, Career Opportunities.

https://www.indianola.k12.ia.us/departments/human-resources-2/job-opportunities/

post_text: An update from Jen Wolf, IHS Life Skills Teacher: The Indianola High School Special Olympics Team has their state competition today. They did a great job and showed Excellent sportsmanship! In the 16-18 age group Antonio Lenguadoro earned 1st place, Ashley Ahren earned 3rd place, and CJ Norfleet earned 6th place. In the 12-15 age group Justyne Easton earned 3rd place. It was an awesome day!

post_text:
Information from Middle School Art Instructor Lisa Smith:

The Lions Club sponsors this poster contest, which encourages young people worldwide to express their visions of peace. This year's theme is “Journey of Peace”. Each poster is judged on originality, artistic merit and communication of the theme.
Congratulations to the following IMS students who placed at the local level: Chloe Chaplin- 3rd place, Ryker Burgin- 2nd place and Ceci McDonald- 1st Place. Ceci’s poster is on its way to the next level of competition. Peace Posters were on display in the Field House lobby in November and 15 of those will be displayed at Redeemer Lutheran Church's art gallery after that. Winners were recognized at the Veteran's Day Assembly.
